body_class: "is-iconography"
---

h1 Iconography

section.mtl
  h2.mbm SVG Menu Icons

  ul
    - design_token("iconography", category: "svg-menu-icon").each do |prop|
      li.dib.mrm.mbm.tac
        figure.b-icon.b-icon-menu
          svg data-svg="#{prop.name}"
            use class="#{prop.name}" xlink:href="#{'#' + prop.value}"
          figcaption.mtm
            code
              = prop.value

  .g-row
    .g-col-12
      h5.mtm.mbxs
        | Markup
      p.mts
        | SVG assets should be preferably <a href="https://css-tricks.com/svg-sprites-use-better-icon-fonts/" taregt="_blank">bundled as sprites (symbols)</a> for organization and cleaner markup.

  .g-row
    .g-col-12
      h5.mtm.mbxs
        | Styles
      p.mts
        | Navigation SVG icons respond to mouse hovering with a change of their color scheme. Since they're being instantiated as a result of the sprite technique mentioned above, targetting SVG components separately demands a few requirements:
      ul.mts.plm
        li
          p Icons should be mostly based on stroked elements, no filled areas.
        li.mts
          p <code>stroke</code> and <code>fill</code> presentation attributes should be removed from the SVG source file on the uppermost grouping element level (e.g.: <code>&lt;g&gt;</code>).
        li.mts
          p Style changes should be applied directly to the <code>use</code> element.
        li.mtm
          = code('sass') do
            |
              figure
                svg use
                  fill: transparent
                  stroke: $b-color

                &:hover
                  svg use
                    stroke: $b-color

section.mtl
  h2.mbm FontAwesome Icons

  ul
    - design_token("iconography", category: "font-awesome-icon").each do |prop|
      li.dib.mrm.mbm.tac
        .b-icon
          i.fa.fa-5x class="#{prop.value}"
          code.mtm
            = prop.value